 REACTION MODELING IN FAST NEUTRON RANGE                          2625 1451
 ---------------------------------------                          2625 1451
                                                                  2625 1451
 The fast region calculations were performed using the EMPIRE     2625 1451
 code, which is a comprehensive package that integrates into a    2625 1451
 single system a number of important physical modules and         2625 1451
 evaluation tools. We have adopted coupled channel (CC)           2625 1451
 calculations in the incident channel and for the direct          2625 1451
 inelastic scattering to collective levels. In addition, we       2625 1451
 have allowed for the Distorted Wave Born Approximation (DWBA)    2625 1451
 to populate presumably collective levels which are not           2625 1451
 included in the ground state band used in the CC calculations    2625 1451
 to adjust neutron emission spectra in the high energy range.     2625 1451
 For the preequilibrium (PE) emission employed the classical      2625 1451
 exciton model (PCROSS module) because of its higher              2625 1451
 flexibility in modeling neutron spectra compared with the        2625 1451
 physically more advanced, but also more rigid quantum            2625 1451
 mechanical models. The same module was also used for the PE      2625 1451
 emission of protons and gammas as well as for PE emission of     2625 1451
 clusters, the latter taking advantage of the Iwamoto-Harada      2625 1451
 model.                                                           2625 1451
                                                                  2625 1451
 The Hauser-Feshbach formulation of the statistical model was     2625 1451
 employed to follow sequential emission of particles from the     2625 1451
 compound nucleus (CN). The elastic and inelastic angular         2625 1451
 distributions of neutrons emitted from the CN were calculated    2625 1451
 using the Blatt-Biedenharn formalism. The width fluctuation      2625 1451
 factor was accounted for within HRTW formalism applied up to     2625 1451
 12.0 MeV incident neutrons. Compound nucleus and direct cross    2625 1451
 sections were added incoherently.                                2625 1451
                                                                  2625 1451
 Gilbert-Cameron model for level-density has been adopted due     2625 1451
 to it performance on the 56Fe(n,p) reaction that is extremely    2625 1451
 sensitive to level densities. Level density parameters were      2625 1451
 fitted to reproduce the asymptotic behavior of discrete          2625 1451
 levels, as well as to correctly describe the observed cross      2625 1451
 sections.                                                        2625 1451
                                                                  2625 1451
 Complete g-ray cascades for every excited nucleus were           2625 1451
 calculated using M1, E1 and E2 electromagnetic transitions.      2625 1451
 g-strength functions for E1 transitions from the RIPL3 MLO1      2625 1451
 formulation by Pluyko.                                           2625 1451
 Occasionally, we resorted to energy-dependent parameter          2625 1451
 scaling or tuning factors, available in the EMPIRE code, to      2625 1451
 account for model deficiencies. These corrections were           2625 1451
 typically on the level of 1-2% or less and can be found in the   2625 1451
 input files. Whenever possible the reaction model parameters     2625 1451
 used in the 54Fe evaluation were kept consistent with those      2625 1451
 used in the 56Fe evaluation.                                     2625 1451
